## Correlating numbers with a cholesky decomposition of a correlation matrix.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
eg <- rethinking::rlkjcorr(1, 2, 1)
cc <- chol(eg)

zz <- matrix(data = rnorm(2000), ncol = 2)
plot(zz)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-19-1.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
cor(zz)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
            [,1]        [,2]
[1,] 1.000000000 0.005528595
[2,] 0.005528595 1.000000000
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
rr <- t(cc) %*% t(zz)
plot(t(rr))
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-19-2.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
cor(t(rr))[1,2]
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] -0.8276924
```
:::
:::


The LKJ prior distribution is a prior over correlation matrices


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# rethinking::rlkjcorr(1, 5, .3)
```
:::
